### CSS Selectors with HTML

-> A CSS selector tells the browser: 'Select this HTML element and apply these styles"
# Example:
# HTML
<h1>Welcome to Algonex</h1>
# CSS
h1 {
    color: blue;
}  --> The <h1> text becomes blue

1. Universal Selector (*) - Selects every element on the page

# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<p>Paragraph</p>
<button>Click Me</button>

# CSS
* {
    margin: 0;
    padding: 0;
    box-sizing: border-box;
} -> Used in almost every professional project as a CSS reset

2. Element (Tag) Selector - Targets every occurrence of a specific HTML tag.
# HTML
<h1>Heading</h1>
<h1>Another Heading</h1>
<p>Paragraph</p>

# CSS
h1 {
    color: red;
}
p {
    color: green;
}

3. Class Selector (.) - One of the most commonly used selectors.
# HTML
<h1 class="title">Welcome</h1>
<h2 class="title">Frontend</h2>

# CSS
.title {
    color: blue;
} -> Both elements are styled

4. ID Selector (#) - Targets a single unique element
# HTML
<h1 id="main-title">
    Welcome
</h1>

# CSS
#main-title {
    color: purple;
} -> IDs should generally be unique within a page

